[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there written anywhere an account of the structure needed on a topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> in order for the category of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span>-points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> to acquire the structure of an orthogonal factorization system (naturally in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span>... in some sense)?</p>",
        "id": 308029646,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667588281
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd be happy to restrict attention to the case where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> classifies an essentially algebraic theory.</p>",
        "id": 308029718,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667588301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe this is a reasonable enough thing to ask for without a specific motivation, but my motivating example would be <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>C</mi><mi>R</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>g</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal B = BCRing</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">BCR</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">in</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span></span></span></span>, the classifying topos for commutative rings. Here, the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span>-points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> have a (localization, conservative) factorization system, which should be functorial in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span> in the sense which is appropriate.</p>",
        "id": 308030490,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667588559
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Have you looked at Lurie's \"fractured <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-topoi\" (SAG chapters 20, 21)?</p>",
        "id": 308033935,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1667589928
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>&amp; specifically Theorem 21.3.0.1 <a href=\"https://www.math.ias.edu/~lurie/papers/SAG-rootfile.pdf\">here</a></p>",
        "id": 308034183,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1667590023
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Mathieu Anel and I thought about this topic a while back but I would have to refresh my memory--you might write to him and see what he has to say.</p>",
        "id": 308035047,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1667590330
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh nice! I was looking there, but had not yet come across that theorem, thanks! (Although now looking at the title of Section 21.3 it's clear I wasn't looking hard enough!)</p>",
        "id": 308044202,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667593978
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So Lurie shows that a fractured <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-topos gives rise to such factorization systems (where reindexing preserves <em>both</em> classes)</p>",
        "id": 308044323,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667594031
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wonder if a converse is to be expected...</p>",
        "id": 308044345,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667594040
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"282691\">@Axel Osmond</span> do you have some sufficient conditions in the 1-topos case?</p>",
        "id": 308101286,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1667635167
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>thanks for the notification <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277473\">@Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span>  !<br>\nIf you have an essentially algebraic theory $\\mathbb{T}$, any left generated factorization system on $\\mathbb{T}[Set]$ will extend to a  factorization system in the category of models of any Grothendieck topos, and both the left and right classes will be stable under inverse image (and also actually direct image). A left generated factorization system is just a factorization system where the left class is obtained as the inductive completion of a set of finitely presented maps, which by the way can always be chosen to be saturated under composition, right cancellation, and finite colimits. You then obtain the factorization of a map $f : B \\rightarrow A$ under a given object by taking the filtered colimit of all its possible factorization through a pushout under $B$  of a finitely presented left map. This is done in detail in  Anel \"Grothendieck topology from factorization systems\" and Coste \"Topos, Tripes and spectra\".  You can find it also in detail in the first chapter of my thesis (and the connection with geometries in the 3rd chapter).</p>",
        "id": 308140730,
        "sender_full_name": "Axel Osmond",
        "timestamp": 1667654839
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"282691\">Axel Osmond</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos-theory/topic/Factorization.20system.20on.20points/near/308140730\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>thanks for the notification <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277473\">Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span>  !<br>\nIf you have an essentially algebraic theory $\\mathbb{T}$, any left generated factorization system on $\\mathbb{T}[Set]$ will extend to a  factorization system in the category of models of any Grothendieck topos, and both the left and right classes will be stable under inverse image (and also actually direct image). A left generated factorization system is just a factorization system where the left class is obtained as the inductive completion of a set of finitely presented maps, which by the way can always be chosen to be saturated under composition, right cancellation, and finite colimits. You then obtain the factorization of a map $f : B \\rightarrow A$ under a given object by taking the filtered colimit of all its possible factorization through a pushout under $B$  of a finitely presented left map. This is done in detail in  Anel \"Grothendieck topology from factorization systems\" and Coste \"Topos, Tripes and spectra\".  You can find it also in detail in the first chapter of my thesis (and the connection with geometries in the 3rd chapter).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thanks, that's great! So in the case where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> classifies an essentially-algebraic theory, you can induce a factorization system on points by starting from a factorization system on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>-points which is generated by finitely-presentable maps. </p>\n<p>Now let me get greedy. I wonder if there is a way of packaging this data which I can more easily make sense of from a \"toposes as generalized spaces\" sort of perspective?</p>\n<p>Toward that end, here's a wildly speculative analogy. Let's think of a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> as being like a \"directed space\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. The objects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> correspond to points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, and the morphisms of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> correspond to \"paths\" in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. Suppose that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is equipped with an orthogonal factorization system <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">L</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\mathcal L, \\mathcal R)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">L</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. Then I claim that what <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">L</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\mathcal L, \\mathcal R)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">L</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is giving you is a notion of \"shortness\" or \"boundedness\" of paths, in the sense that a morphism in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">L</span></span></span></span> should be thought of as a path which is \"short\"/ \"bounded\". The closure properties of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">L</span></span></span></span> are consistent with this: identity paths are \"short\", a composite of \"short\" paths is \"short\", a small colimit of \"short\" paths is \"short\".  The cobase-change of a \"short\" path is some kind of \"translation\" of that path, and so also \"short\"; right cancellation also kind of makes sense.</p>\n<p>One sort of intuition I want to have is that \"short\" might mean \"of length less than <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span>\" for some fixed <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r \\geq 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> -- but if this intuition is to be used, we should think of the notion of \"length\" as coming from some kind of \"ultrametric\" rather than an \"archimedean\" metric (hence the closure under composition). In this sense, maybe a notion of \"boundedness\" is a better intuition.</p>\n<p>So from this perspective, putting a factorization system on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>G</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C = Geom(\\mathcal X, \\mathcal B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">eo</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is endowing the points of this mapping \"space\" with some kind of binary notion of \"closeness\". In the case at hand, we have that a notion of \"closeness\" on the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span></span></span></span>-points <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Geom(\\mathcal S, \\mathcal B)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">eo</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> induces such a notion on all mapping spaces -- presumably the resulting factorization systems are all kind of \"levelwise\"?</p>\n<p>Ok, I realize now I don't know where I'm going with this, but I wonder if that sort of picture makes sense to anyone? (And optimistically, does it maybe even tie in with these \"theories of spectra\" somehow?)</p>",
        "id": 308152030,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1667659904
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like the picture, and it can probably be interpreted literally in something like the Butz-Moerdijk construction of a topological groupoid from the category of points (although I don't know of any resource for understanding those groupoids concretely enough to make such a picture \"useful\")</p>\n<p>On the logical side, one could probably come up with sufficient structural criteria on a theory to derive factorization systems of a given form, especially when a factorization system exists already at the level of finitely presentable models. Lots of theories have an \"injection-surjection\" factorization, for instance, which must surely be definable under mild conditions.</p>",
        "id": 308161259,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1667664343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I never thought of those factorization systems as expressing some notion of closeness, so before discussing this, I would rather recall a bit how those factorizations involved in the theory of spectrum can be understood either from a logical and a geometric point of view : </p>\n<ul>\n<li>geometrically, the left maps  are dual to some saturated compact inclusions (amongst which the finitely presented one code for compact opens), while the right maps encode some notion of connectedness. This is related to the (connected, truncated) pattern that encompasses a lot of examples of factorization systems in categories of spaces, in particular various factorization systems of geometric morphisms.  </li>\n<li>but left-generated factorization systems also have a logical interpretation: the finitely presented left maps from which the system is generated code for a class of function symbols (for they are dual to some provably functional formulas in the syntactic category of your theory) whose pushouts under arbitrary objects are to be seen as their interpretation in those objects  ; on the other side, right maps are those that reflects the objects constructed from those function symbols. For instance, localizations create new invertibles and conservative morphisms reflect those latter. <br>\nHowever those explanations make sense in the context of a spectral construction, where not all objects of your ambient category are to be seen as points for your geometry - only a distinguished class satisfying some condition relating them to your right class - e.g. : local rings.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 308192148,
        "sender_full_name": "Axel Osmond",
        "timestamp": 1667686633
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277991\">@Tim Campion</span>  but if I understand well, the view point your are describing is quite different as you want to see morphisms in the factorization system to express data between points. So let us describe in detail, from a somewhat ionadic point of view, what can of topological situation this could express. </p>\n<p>Morphisms between (generalized) points of a topos should be seen somewhat encoding specialization order; then a factorization system would distinguish two kinds of specializations between points, obeying dual cancellations properties and stability under (co)limits. For a topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo>≃</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathcal{E} \\simeq Sh(\\mathcal{C}, J)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">h</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, basic compact open for the topology on the points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span>  - which correspond to objects of the site <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span>- induce discrete opfibrations of points through the evaluation functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">S</mi><mrow><mi>p</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathcal{C} \\rightarrow \\mathcal{S}^{pt(\\mathcal{E}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.075em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">pt</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, where the lifting property of opfibration tells you that a witness $a$ that a point <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> X_1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> lies in an basic open <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span></span></span></span> is sent along a specialization map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f :X_1 \\rightarrow X_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> to a witness that its codomain <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> X_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0785em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is also in this open <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span></span></span></span> (\"open are upclosed\" for the specialization). </p>\n<p>But now if you have a distinguished class of maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> in the site (as in the case of a left generated system), this can be seen as a distinguished class of inclusions between basic compact opens of your basis, stipulating that an compact open is \"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span>-sufficiently\" included inside of another. From a logical point of view, seeing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span> as the syntactic site of some geometric theory <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathbb{T}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">T</span></span></span></span> and hence <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> as a class of functional symbols, this notion for a basic open to being \"sufficiently\" inside another expresses that you only need operations coded by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\Lambda </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> to produce witnesses that a point <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> lies inside a basic open <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> sufficiently containing another one  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> from a witness that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> was in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>: in other words, this is inclusion that can be \"tested\" at the level of points in term of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Λ</span></span></span></span> operations.</p>",
        "id": 308195774,
